The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Thursday, January 08, 2004 				 Mufti taps sapphire treasure
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Jammu, Jan. 7: The Jammu and Kashmir government has decided to float global tenders for extraction of sapphire from the Padder mines in Doda district.																								The government wants to utilise the potential of the mines, which have a sapphire reserve worth crores of rupees, to the maximum not only to earn but also improve the plight of the people. This is the first time that the government has come up with the idea.																								A comprehensive mining plan will be drawn up immediately to tap this vast mineral wealth. A decision to this effect was taken at a review meeting of the industries and commerce department yesterday. 																								Chief minister Mufti Mohammad Sayeed has ordered that teams of experts be sent to Padder to decide on modalities for the preparation of an integrated mining plan, which will soon be followed by the floating of tenders worldwide for the excavation of sapphire. Pointing out the states abundant mineral resources  with 3,200 million tonnes of limestone and 95 million tonnes of gypsum  Mufti said this calls for a well-conceived policy.																								The state has also received 114 proposals for industrial investment worth Rs 900 crore after the Peoples Democratic Party government took over in November 2002. These are expected to generate employment for 6,000 people. It will also participate in exhibitions in Germany, Dubai and the UK to promote popular handicrafts of the state.																								Greater focus would be laid on Dubai as it would also promote tourist flow from the Gulf countries.
